The safety of this change hinges on whether the subsequent code relies on the original `sname` value before the conditional assignment. In this specific instance, it does indeed depend on the previous `sname`. Consequently, I hold reservations about this modification and anticipate that it may result in failed tests on CI pipeline.
I think 10\*1000\*1000 here is forcePreemptNS. For example, **pd.syscallwhen + forcePreemptNS> now** means that if the syscall runs for more than 10ms (forcePreemptNS), it can be preempted.

I agree that interpreting empty lines is important for single field cases. The current implementation requires a fixed number of fields in some cases though. So in those cases, an error should be thrown when an empty line is seen but the "header row/first row" has more than one field or FieldsPerRecord is greater than 1.

This function is guaranteed to not return an error.
The previous call to regexp.MatchString didn't fail, so this one can't.
(Errors only depend on the first argument.)

Probably the right fix is to do:
  match, _ = regexp.MatchString(want, got.e)
to indicate we know the error can't happen.

Sure, this is probably the right pattern in this instance.
